<div id="comment_244612993" class="brown_comment">
  <div class="xhr_comment_photo">
    	<a alt="Lisa" href="/user/show/72141784-lisa"><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1507052997p1/72141784.jpg" alt="72141784" /></a>
  </div>
  <div class="xhr_comment_body">
    <a style="font-weight:bold" href="/user/show/72141784-lisa">Lisa</a>

      
<span id="freeTextContainer11602759877442960391">I appreciate your edited preamble. I&apos;ve been listening to this book for a few days now and, every once in a while, Haidt will frame an observation in </span>
  <span id="freeText11602759877442960391" style="display:none">I appreciate your edited preamble. I've been listening to this book for a few days now and, every once in a while, Haidt will frame an observation in a way that makes me think, "This man seems to have some significant biases/mental blocks that he doesn't appear to be aware of." For example, I've just hit the section of the book were he argues that the need to gossip has been the primary driver for human brain development over time. The claim seems unusually specific, very scientifically unlikely, and quite cynical. Why the psychologically charged and limited-in-scope "to gossip" and not the more neutral " to communicate?" He doesn't seem interested in neutralizing the framing and indeed doubles down by the time he starts talking about his grad student's research. At first, it caught me off gaurd because I thought the book started off with some interesting points and analysis with an open/curious/humble tone which I appreciate. But there have now been a couple times where I've been taken aback by these random spikes of biased and bitter framing. It's like finding a clump of hair in an otherwise enjoyable soup. I feel somewhat validated in my intuitions by your review edit.<br /><br />I think I'll continue exploring the book, but definitely will be a bit more gaurded.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11602759877442960391" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

